arch:property.oc:show_val: Locus 51 is the soil directly below the floor (Locus 49) of the covered pool. The soil is a fine compacted soil of silt and sand (Munsell 7.5 YR 3/3 dark brown). Small amounts of bone, pottery, and small stones are included in the soil. This soil locus, and those below it in the pool are the result of dumping, meant to fill in the pool after it went out of use. It is phased to Stage 4, with the covering of the pool and other post-363 alterations to the Complex.

Phase X: Site abandonment after major collapse dating to the Byzantine period from the CE 4th to 5th c. New drainage systems are installed including that associated with the newly built west precinct wall.
Post-363 reworking of the Complex, including blockage of doorways and the covering of the ornamental pool.
3.20 m north south -by- 1.35 m east west (exposed).
Soil and leveling course below the floor of the covered pool
